**Status:** In Progress → Closed as TP  
**Date:** 30-05-2026

## 1. Alert Fields I Learned Today
Working inside the alert panel for first time. Each field has a purpose in SOC:

**Status**: Shows what stage alert is at
- New: Alert just came in, no one picked it yet
- In Progress: I assigned it to myself, started investigating
- Closed: Work done, saved and closed the case

**Verdict**: My final call after investigation. This is most important field.
- True Positive TP: Alert was real. Actual malware/attack happened. Must escalate to L2
- False Positive FP: SIEM gave false alarm. Nothing malicious. Close it and tell engineer to tune rule
- Benign Positive: Attack happened but got blocked. No damage done

Note to self: TP = Real danger | FP = Fake alarm. Can't mix these up.

**Severity**: How serious SIEM thinks this is
- Critical/High: Check right now. My alert was High priority
- Medium/Low: Can wait. Like normal port scans

**Assignee**: Owner of alert. Mine shows "You L1" so I have to close it. SOC rule: "Jo uthayega wahi band karega"

**Analyst Comment**: This is my report for L2 team. Write what I checked, what I found, what action I took.
 
## 2. Key Takeaway
Clicked Save and closed my first alert as L1 analyst. Felt good.
Biggest lesson: Verdict decides everything. If I mark TP as FP, real attack gets missed. 
If I mark FP as TP, L2 team wastes time. Need to be sure before closing
